---
description: Reproducible R and Python data-science conventions (environmental, ecological, geospatial)
alwaysApply: true
---

# Priorities
Optimize for code that reads top-to-bottom and reruns cleanly — not for abstraction,
generality, or "production" polish. This is reproducible analysis, not a software product.

# System / environment
- Primary host: Aurora (aurora.nceas.ucsb.edu) — a shared, multi-user NCEAS research
  server reached over SSH. Many people use it at once, so resource discipline matters
  (see Parallel & multiprocessing).
- CPU: 2x AMD EPYC 9634 -> 168 physical cores / 336 logical (2 threads/core).
- RAM: ~2.2 TiB.
- Work may also run on local machines; the shared-server utilization caps below apply
  specifically when on a shared server like Aurora.

# Communication
- Be concise and scannable; lead with the answer; don't restate code back.
- When directions are unclear, ask clarifying questions — and note how the request
  could have been phrased more clearly.

# Working with code (general)
- Make only changes that were requested or are clearly understood and directly related
  to the task. Don't touch unrelated code.
- Strongly prefer common, well-documented, standard packages and techniques.
- Don't assume a package or function exists from memory. Confirm it's installed in the
  active environment before importing, and verify the specific function/argument exists
  in the installed version rather than guessing.
- Never fabricate data, results, statistics, or citations. When inferring something
  rather than knowing it, say so.

# Scope & file discipline
- Edit the currently open file. Never create a new file to hold changes unless
  explicitly asked. Don't write single-use throwaway scripts.
- When fixing a bug, exhaust the existing implementation before introducing a new
  pattern or library. If switching is unavoidable, delete the old version — leave no
  duplicate logic behind.

# Simplicity & abstraction
- Prefer the simplest solution that works. Don't wrap a few lines in a function or
  class without a real reason (no premature abstraction).
- Don't extract functions, constants, or settings into a separate sourced/imported
  file unless explicitly asked to refactor that way.
- Avoid duplicate or parallel implementations across the codebase; don't reinvent what
  already exists. This is about architecture, NOT within-script style — inside a single
  file, prefer readable inline steps over extracted helpers, even at the cost of a
  little repetition.

# Script structure (literate & linear)
- Write every file to read top-to-bottom as a self-contained narrative that runs in a
  fresh session. A reader should follow the full chain of reasoning to the conclusion by
  reading it start to finish, with no indirection to chase.
- Use this layout, in order:
    1. Header comment: purpose, inputs, outputs.
    2. Settings — every tunable parameter/variable (chunk size, worker count, flags,
       thresholds) as well-formatted, commented variables, editable in one place.
    3. File paths — every path the script uses, declared up front.
    4. Body, in numbered sequential stages.
- Mark major sections with a foldable, visually bold divider that opens with a title
  and emoji over an equals bar:
    R:        # ============================================================
              # ⚙️ Settings ----
              # ============================================================
    Python:   # %% ⚙️ Settings
              # ============================================================
  (The `----` / `# %%` makes the section foldable in the editor outline.)

# Multi-file pipelines
- When scripts in a folder chain together or build on each other, number them in run
  order with a zero-padded prefix: 01_, 02_, 03_, …
- When inserting a new step between existing ones, renumber the whole sequence so it
  stays correct and contiguous. Don't use 01b_, suffixes, or out-of-order numbers.
- Declare each script's inputs and outputs in its header.

# Project layout & housekeeping
- Standard project folders: scripts/ (the numbered analysis pipeline), logs/ (run
  logs, process output, agent-monitored logs, the change record, and temp/scratch),
  and archive/ (retired code and files). Raw data and derived outputs both live in
  dedicated locations outside the project folder (see Outputs).
- Archive, don't delete. When a script or block of code is retired by a rewrite or is
  no longer needed, move it into archive/ rather than deleting it. Same for any file or
  folder being removed during cleanup — relocate it into archive/ instead of hard-
  deleting. Keep archive/ organized (e.g., dated or mirroring the original structure),
  not a dumping ground.
- Keep the main folder clean. Move logs, temp, and scratch files out of the project
  root into logs/ so they don't clog it; don't scatter throwaway output at the top level.
- Keep a change record. Maintain a dated log of structural changes — what was archived,
  moved, or removed, and why — so the folder's history stays recoverable. This matters
  for agentic work, where it's easy to lose track of how things evolved.
    Suggested: logs/CHANGELOG.md, appended with "## <YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM PT> — <summary>".
- Deletion still requires confirmation (see Agent guardrails); archiving is the
  default, safe alternative to removing work.

# READMEs
Maintain two READMEs (never one per script); a single expansive README covering both
is fine, and it's okay for it to be long:
- Project README at the working-directory root — the top-level "what's going on here"
  document: project purpose, the pipeline and run order, the overall workflow, folder
  structure, and where data and outputs live.
- Data README in the output/data location: documents the data so it can be USED
  without reading any script — file layout, a data dictionary (fields/bands, units,
  ranges, nodata), spatial reference (CRS), temporal coverage, provenance, caveats,
  and the path to the scripts folder where the pipeline that originally created the
  data lives (relative from the data README when possible).
Behavior:
- Create a missing README before finishing work in that area.
- Update the relevant README in the same change set whenever code, outputs, fields,
  paths, or steps change.
- Audit before completing: fix anything stale and note what changed.

# Outputs
- Assume derived outputs are written to a dedicated location outside the working
  directory, not into the project folder. If that location isn't already specified in
  the code or the conversation, ask before writing — don't guess a path.

# Comments & narration
- Comment the WHY and the reasoning behind each decision. Narrate non-obvious steps from
  a data-science perspective so a reader understands what's happening. Don't comment
  trivial lines that just restate the code.
- Use emojis in comments and output to aid scanning and understanding.

# Run-log comments (snapshots, not truth)
- After a run, a dated note may be appended recording key observed outcomes of a step to
  make drift visible across future runs:
    # RUN LOG <YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM PT>: <row counts, key stats, extents/CRS, file sizes>
- Treat these as historical snapshots, never as authoritative. The real record of a
  result is the code's actual output. If nearby code changes, flag that a run-log note
  may be stale and offer to update it.

# R
- Follow the tidyverse style guide; snake_case; native pipe |> with one verb per line.
- Prefer a consistent, well-documented ecosystem (e.g. tidyverse + sf/terra). Don't
  shadow base names (data, df, sd, T, c). Don't add dependencies casually.

# Python
- Apply the same readability philosophy: prefer clear, chained data transformations
  written one method per line so the logic reads top-to-bottom. Use well-established,
  well-documented libraries; don't add dependencies casually. Put type hints on
  function signatures. Prefer uv for environments.

# Reproducibility & data integrity
- Pin dependencies (renv / uv). Use relative paths via here(). Set seeds and comment
  them. Treat raw data as read-only — write derived outputs to separate paths.
- Never silently drop rows, recode values, change units, or reproject. Make any such
  transformation explicit, commented, and called out plainly.

# Geospatial & CRS handling
CRS errors are silent, so be deliberate.
- Verify the CRS on load rather than assuming it, and check it before and after
  transformations. Don't confuse relabeling a CRS with reprojecting it. Validate that
  transformations succeeded and that CRS assumptions hold (e.g. sanity-check coordinate
  ranges, extent, or geometry after reprojecting).
- Measure in a projected CRS rather than geographic degrees, choosing one suited to what's
  being measured (e.g. equal-area for area, equidistant for distance). Different steps may
  use different CRSs.
- Bring layers to a common CRS before multi-layer operations, and mind the datum, not just
  the projection.
- When reprojecting rasters, match the resampling method to the data (categorical vs
  continuous) and avoid needless repeated resampling.
- Note the CRS of outputs.

# Formatting
- Write clean, readable, well-structured code — naming, sectioning, and logical flow are
  part of the job. Let Air (R) and Ruff (Python) own mechanical layout — whitespace,
  quotes, line-wrapping — and don't hand-tune or fight what they'll normalize on save.

# Logging & output
- Timestamp every print/log statement in Pacific Time:
    R:      format(Sys.time(), "%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S %Z", tz = "America/Los_Angeles")
    Python: datetime.now(ZoneInfo("America/Los_Angeles")).strftime("%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S %Z")

# Parallel & multiprocessing
Applies to parallel R/Python. Expose controls in Settings (workers, chunk, mem cap, nice).

- Utilization caps (hard):
    - CPU/RAM (shared): total load — cap 75%, target ~70%. Pre-flight live metrics; back off if crowded; re-check on long runs.
    - GPU (single-user): max throughput while you hold the device; host-side workers still obey CPU/RAM caps.
    - Measure: `nproc`, `/proc/loadavg`, `free -h` (or psutil).

- Flat memory profile via chunking: load one small chunk -> reduce/filter immediately ->
  keep only the small result -> combine at the end. Don't load everything then process.
  Don't gate on "free RAM before launch" alone — workers pass the gate, then all spike at
  once and crash the box.

- Hard per-worker memory cap at the OS level so a runaway worker dies cleanly instead of
  triggering the OOM killer and taking down the server. Lower CPU priority (nice) so
  interactive users aren't starved.

- Guarantee worker cleanup even on crash (context manager / on.exit / stop the cluster).
  Never leave zombie workers.

- Wrap worker logic in try/except (tryCatch) and return a structured status object. Never
  fail silently inside a subprocess; catch the memory-cap error explicitly.

- Pass file paths and small primitives to workers, not large objects (DataFrames, arrays,
  loaded rasters) — each worker serializes its own copy, multiplying memory.

- Match the tool to the bottleneck: processes for CPU-bound work (raster math, array ops —
  true parallelism); threads/async for I/O-bound work (downloads, disk, APIs).

- Validate before scaling up — either run serially or do a smoke test with a low
  worker count — since subprocess errors are cryptic.

- Watch fork vs spawn: forking copies parent state and open handles and can crash
  libraries like GDAL/rasterio/terra/CUDA. On mysterious segfaults or hangs, switch to
  spawn (Python) or a PSOCK cluster instead of fork/mclapply (R) — at the cost of slower
  startup and requiring all arguments to be serializable.
  Tooling: Python — resource.setrlimit (mem cap), os.nice, maxtasksperchild.
           R — unix::rlimit_as (mem cap), tools::psnice, PSOCK clusters for spawn-like
           isolation.

# Long-run progress
Long jobs: progress must be easy to see from chat — prefer tqdm (or similar) with ETA; logged updates are fine if the log streams live here. Before launch, ensure something is observable and say where to watch; flag stalls.

# Agent guardrails
- Never run destructive commands (rm, overwrites, git commit/push, force) or modify
  env/config files without surfacing them first and getting confirmation.
- For consequential or multi-step work, state the plan and pause for confirmation.
